image.altText: A young woman with long dark hair tied back sits on a bench next to an orange e-scooter.

props.synopsis: ACT Policing says the majority of e-scooter riders are doing the right thing but they do have concerns about some behaviour, particularly given how vulnerable they are compared with other road users.

title.children: Violet is one of many Canberrans who rides e-scooters and she admits to not always doing the right thing

image.altText: The Alexander Maconochie Centre in the ACT.

props.synopsis: A coroner examining the suicide of a detainee at Canberra's jail has found the ACT had accommodated prisoners in cells they knew to be unsafe.

title.children: Luke was placed in a jail cell with a known suicide risk during COVID. He died the next day

image.altText: A composite image of Linda Reynolds and Brittany Higgins.

props.synopsis: The witnesses have wrapped up their evidence and the legal teams are preparing their final pitches to the judge as the mammoth defamation trial between WA Senator Linda Reynolds and her ex-staffer Brittany Higgins nears its end. Here's what we've learned.

title.children: Here's what we know after three weeks of the Linda Reynolds vs Brittany Higgins defamation trial

image.altText: Green grass on a rolling hill at the national arboretum

props.synopsis: Tree pollen season is already triggering hay fever in the national capital, and the start of grass pollen season could be just weeks away, according to experts.

title.children: Arboretum photos indicate Canberra could have 'earlier and above average grass pollen season'

image.altText: A still shot from a police bodycam showing a man sitting in a car with his hands up being tasered.

props.synopsis: ACT Supreme Court Justice Louise Taylor says Nathaniel Coulter, 22, was tasered despite the fact he was sitting in a car wearing a seat belt and in a submissive position after a dramatic car chase.

title.children: 'Used to punish': Judge criticises tasering by police in Canberra man's arrest

image.altText: The scene of a car crash at night.

props.synopsis: A 15-year-old charged with the death of a man in a collision earlier this year is set to face another charge, after a passenger injured in the crash died this week.

title.children: Teenager facing more charges after a second passenger dies from Barton Highway crash injuries

image.altText: A middle aged white woman with long blonde hair sitting on a park bench

props.synopsis: Annual drug overdose deaths in Australia have almost doubled over the past 20 years. Advocates say it's time governments change the way they tackle the issue.

title.children: When police came to her door, Jen was worried her daughter had been arrested. The reality was far worse

image.altText: Chris Pearson portrait

props.synopsis: An inquiry ordered following a Four Corners investigation into the Public Trustee concluded that the agency's actions "in the main … were appropriate". Refunds and a misplaced account tell a different story.

title.children: Facing questions from the ABC, the Public Trustee found a client's misplaced account containing $73,000

image.altText: Lia Finocchiaro smiles and celebrates the election victory.

props.synopsis: The NT's new incoming chief minister Lia Finocchiaro and the CLP have won a commanding majority government, with a mandate to lower crime rates and fix the territory's lagging economy.

title.children: Landslide victory for the CLP in NT election, as party decimates Labor in Darwin heartland

image.altText: Albanese and Bullock

props.synopsis: Treasurer Jim Chalmers says he won't abolish the government's power to overrule the Reserve Bank, but he will try to restrict its ability to be used.

title.children: The government will keep its power to overrule the RBA. Even though it's never been used

image.altText: Black writing on a white piece of paper with blue reflections

props.synopsis: Despite cuts to regulated power prices, some consumers are paying more than double the benchmark. Advocates say the system is broken.

title.children: Advocates decry 'failing' protections for energy consumers as some pay 'double' benchmark price

image.altText: Jonathan Simonds wears anti-war badges including one that says 'not another bomb'.

props.synopsis: While America's Democratic diehards enjoyed pep talks and pop music at their party-vibes convention this week, a smaller panel event on the sidelines was striking a very different tone.

title.children: Why some Democrats think a 'boneheaded mistake' could threaten Kamala Harris's election chances

image.altText: A yellow sign says footpath closed and yellow

props.synopsis: Seismologist Michael Turnbull predicts "reasonably sized" earthquakes of at least magnitude 3 could hit the area for the next couple of months.

title.children: Aftershocks expected to rattle the NSW Upper Hunter for months

image.altText: Half a dozen special police forces stand in full helmet and camo gear

props.synopsis: German police detain a man they say went on a stabbing rampage in the west German city of Solingen, killing three people and injuring eight others.

title.children: Suspect in fatal knife attack at German festival arrested, officials say

image.altText: Takuya Shiota wears full PPE including a breathing mask with a white hood tightened around the outside of his face as he cleans.

props.synopsis: Dying a lonely death is an increasing problem in Japan, and it's not just due to its aging population, with a lack of community among the factors isolating people.

title.children: As Japan ages, a terrifying proposition is emerging: Dying alone and no-one finding your body for years

image.altText: A man with dark hair holds the face of a serious looking woman with blonde hair and blue eyes

props.synopsis: Any efforts to kickstart conversations about abuse should be applauded. But as a serious reflection of what domestic violence is really like, It Ends With Us falls short.

title.children: The truth of violent marriages is lost when Hollywood refuses to face the dark reality

image.altText: Australian personnel approach one of the boats at Kuri Bay.

title.children: Reports of illegal foreign fishing vessel in WA's remote north

image.altText: Sunita Williams and Butch WIlmore

props.synopsis: Astronauts Butch Wilmore and Suni Williams — stuck in space since June — will have to wait until next year for a ride home.

title.children: NASA decides astronauts stranded in space will return home in February

image.altText: Two prisoners of war draped in Ukraine flags embrace after being released

props.synopsis: It is the seventh such exchange the UAE has mediated since Russia invaded Ukraine in February 2022.

image.altText: Ruins of a stone building and a more modern building with a tin roof.

props.synopsis: For some people, tasting the pies made in the outback South Australian town of Farina is a bucket-list activity. The pies are cooked in an underground bakery in the otherwise deserted town, with the proceeds going towards restoring Farina's ruins.

image.altText: Tom Gleeson standing with his arms crossed and a serious look on his face. The Hard Quiz has been added behind his head

props.synopsis: Call yourself a Hard Quiz fan? Let's put it to the test.

title.children: Still call yourself a trivia champ? We'll see about that

image.altText: Chris Fagan walking on the Gabba after a Lions' AFL match.

props.synopsis: The Lions get home by 20 points against the Bombers at the Gabba, but coach Chris Fagan is less than impressed as his side turns its attention to the finals.

title.children: 'Shouldn't have been as close as it was': Lions concerned about form after tense win over Bombers

image.altText: Kalyn Ponga holds the ball in both hands during an 2024 NRL match for the Newcastle Knights.

title.children: 'He's just got a look about him': Why Ponga is giving Knights hope of making finals

image.altText: Oscar Piastri with his hands on his head after qualifying at the Dutch Grand Prix.

props.synopsis: Oscar Piastri says he did not "do a good enough job" during qualifying at the Dutch F1 Grand Prix, clearly feeling his McLaren team missed out on locking up the front row of the Zandvoort grid.

title.children: Piastri frustrated after qualifying third for Dutch F1

image.altText: Sun breaks through the trees on the driveway out of Avatar's Abode.

props.synopsis: Safekeepers of Avatar's Abode, a 40-hectare Sunshine Coast property that's dedicated to global spiritual leader Meher Baba, are confident they will preserve the site for centuries.

title.children: A 'hidden jewel' of the Sunshine Coast, this spiritual and ecological sanctuary could be worth $20m

image.altText: To Lam sitting down on a chair with two microphones in front of him on a lectern.

props.synopsis: Former minister of public security To Lam has rapidly ascended to power in Vietnam, taking on two of the four roles considered the "pillars" of the country's political system. Some are already comparing him to Xi Jinping.

title.children: To Lam was once parodied after being fed steak by Salt Bae. He's now the most powerful man in Vietnam

image.altText: BluLink live stream

props.synopsis: Members of the public can now click on a link that is sent to their smartphone when they call triple-0. A limited trial has already been used in cases including the fatal Bondi Junction stabbing in April.

title.children: People who call triple-0 in NSW can now live stream their emergency to police

image.altText: group of police and search crews and police cars

props.synopsis: A man has been found safe and well after surviving three days in the remote Kimberley outback, as temperatures soared past 38 degrees Celsius.

title.children: Man survives three days lost in remote Kimberley outback in searing heat

image.altText: A thumbnail showing different fires caused by battery faults.

props.synopsis: New South Wales has reported 185 lithium ion battery fires up until August this year, with more than six battery fires per week. Fire and Rescue NSW has referred to battery fires as "the fastest growing fire risk" in the state.

image.altText: Belinda, wearing sunglasses and a white and blue dress (Left) and Vienna wearing a blue singlet and sunglasses (right).

props.synopsis: Vienna was diagnosed with Primary Ovarian Insufficiency (POI) at 19. But the lack of awareness about the rare condition is causing severe delays in diagnosis, putting young women's lives at risk.

title.children: Women who experience menopause before 40 can have POI. But many doctors don't know enough about it

image.altText: Two men sit at a desk, one is wearing a green shirt, the other a plaid shirt and headphones.

props.synopsis: A new mental health charity is helping Australian dads overcome loneliness by connecting men through online gaming.

title.children: Taurean hadn't made friends outside of work for 15 years. Then he found a network of dads

image.altText: A man posing alongside a young girl. Both are smiling at the camera.

props.synopsis: It comes one day after the body of Mike Lynch's 18-year-old daughter Hannah was recovered from the site of the shipwreck.

title.children: Manslaughter inquiry launched after sinking of Mike Lynch's family superyacht

image.altText: Sumaya Abu Ghaliba sits on a hospital bed with daylight coming in a window behind her.

props.synopsis: Children like Sumaya are among the thousands estimated to have lost a limb in the nine months of the Gaza war, and doctors say the situation inside some hospitals is so bad they are sometimes amputating without anaesthesia.

image.altText: Machinery digs up the tram tracks along Glenelg's Jetty Road.

props.synopsis: The potentially politically explosive overhaul is the first major shift in commonwealth-state land transport infrastructure funding arrangements since 2019.

image.altText: About 10 women in bathing suits swimming in the sea.

props.synopsis: Before dawn, Williamstown Beach in Melbourne's inner west is alive with the giggles of those braving the winter seawater, who turn out each day regardless of the weather forecasts, or the warnings issued by Victoria's Environment Protection Agency.
